 theory to empirical research, Jordan develops a descent-with-modification perspective on the technology of Northern Hemisphere hunter-gatherers. Case studies from indigenous societies in Northwest Siberia, the Pacific Northwest Coast, and Northern California provide cross-cultural insights related to the evolution of material culture traditions at different social and spatial scales. This book promises new ways of exploring some of the primary factors that generate human cultural diversity in the deep past and through to the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHumanismxHistoryy20th century. 0aHunting and gathering societies. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aPrehistoric peoplesxMaterial culture. 0aSocial evolution. 0aSocial learning. 0aTechnological complexity. 0aTechnology and civilization. 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 70(DE-601)1043470070(DE-588)4023299-2aHandwerk2gnd 70(DE-601)1061153910(DE-588)4066097-7aWildbeuter2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aarchaeology.  acultural diversity.  acultural lineages.  acultural transmission theory.  acumulative change.  adescent with modification.  aglobal history.  ahuman cultural material.  ahuman technology.  ahunter gatherers.  aindigenous societies.  alanguage history.  amaterial culture.  anorthern california.  anorthern hemisphere.  anorthwest siberia.  aoperational sequence.  apacific northwest coast.  asocial learning.  asocial traditions.  asocial.  atechnology.  atradition.  avariability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027692540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095833340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn